Section 1.5: Junior Level Questions & Answers

Q1: What is the difference between QEMU and KVM?

<details>
<summary><b>Answer</b></summary>

QEMU is a userspace program that provides:

· Device emulation (virtio, SATA, NICs, etc.)
· Machine model (PC, virt, etc.)
· I/O handling (block, network)
· User interface (monitor, VNC, etc.)

KVM (Kernel-based Virtual Machine) is a kernel module that provides:

· CPU virtualization (uses hardware extensions)
· Memory management (EPT/NPT)
· Interrupt delivery (APICv)
· Device assignment (VFIO)

Relationship: QEMU uses KVM for CPU and memory virtualization, while QEMU handles I/O emulation. Together, they create a complete VM.

Without KVM: QEMU uses TCG for CPU emulation (slower, but any architecture works)
With KVM: QEMU uses KVM for CPU (faster, needs same architecture as host)

</details>

Q2: Why does QEMU have both target/ and hw/ directories?

<details>
<summary><b>Answer</b></summary>

target/ contains architecture-specific CPU definition:

· CPU state (registers, MMU)
· Instruction translation (TCG)
· KVM implementation for that architecture
· Architecture-specific helpers

hw/ contains device models:

· Devices that work across architectures (virtio, PCI, etc.)
· Machine models (PC, virt, etc.)
· Bus implementations (PCI, I2C, etc.)
· System integration

Separation Benefits:

1. Reusability: Same devices work across architectures
2. Maintainability: Architecture changes don't affect devices
3. Composability: Mix and match CPUs and devices

Example: A virtio-blk device (hw/) works the same way on x86 (target/i386/), ARM (target/arm/), and RISC-V (target/riscv/).

Contrast: target/ changes when adding a new architecture; hw/ changes when adding new devices.

</details>

Q3: What does --enable-kvm do at runtime?

<details>
<summary><b>Answer</b></summary>

--enable-kvm enables KVM acceleration at runtime.

What it does:

1. Opens /dev/kvm to access KVM kernel module
2. Creates a VM via KVM_CREATE_VM ioctl
3. Creates vCPUs via KVM_CREATE_VCPU ioctl
4. Sets up memory (using KVM_SET_USER_MEMORY_REGION)
5. Runs VCPUs using KVM_RUN ioctl

Process flow:

```c
// QEMU KVM initialization
int kvm_init(CPUArchState *env) {
    int fd = open("/dev/kvm", O_RDWR);
    int vm_fd = ioctl(fd, KVM_CREATE_VM, 0);
    for (int i = 0; i < num_cpus; i++) {
        int vcpu_fd = ioctl(vm_fd, KVM_CREATE_VCPU, i);
        // ... setup vCPU
    }
    return 0;
}
```

Without --enable-kvm: Uses TCG (software emulation) - slower but supports any architecture
With --enable-kvm: Uses KVM for CPU - faster but only works when host and guest architectures match

</details>

Q4: What is the QEMU monitor?

<details>
<summary><b>Answer</b></summary>

The QEMU monitor is an interactive console that allows runtime management of the VM.

Access Methods:

· -monitor stdio (standard input)
· -monitor telnet:localhost:4444,server,nowait (over network)
· -monitor vnc (via VNC)
· -monitor unix:/tmp/monitor.sock,server,nowait (Unix socket)

Common Commands:

Command Purpose
info cpus List vCPUs
info registers CPU registers
info block Block devices
info network Network devices
info pci PCI devices
info qtree Device tree
device_add Add device at runtime
device_del Remove device at runtime
migrate Live migration
screendump Screenshot
sendkey Send keyboard input
system_reset Reset the VM
system_powerdown Shutdown the VM
stop / cont Pause/resume VM
qemu-io Block I/O commands

Use Cases:

· Debugging (check device state)
· Hotplug (add/remove devices)
· Live migration (monitor + control)
· Automation (via QMP)

</details>

Q5: What are the main QEMU subsystems?

<details>
<summary><b>Answer</b></summary>

5 Main Subsystems:

1. CPU Subsystem (target/ + accel/):
   · CPU emulation (TCG) or virtualization (KVM)
   · Instruction translation
   · Exception/interrupt handling
   · MMU management
2. Memory Subsystem (softmmu/physmem.c):
   · Physical memory management
   · Memory regions (RAM, MMIO, ROM)
   · Memory mapping (GPA → HVA)
   · DMA management
3. Device Subsystem (hw/):
   · Device models (virtio-blk, etc.)
   · Bus infrastructure (PCI, etc.)
   · Hotplug support
   · Device tree (QOM)
4. I/O Subsystem (block/, net/, softmmu/ioport.c):
   · Block device I/O (virtio-blk, etc.)
   · Network I/O (virtio-net, etc.)
   · Port I/O (inb/outb)
   · MMIO (read/write to devices)
5. Monitor/Control Subsystem (softmmu/monitor.c):
   · QEMU monitor
   · QMP (QEMU Management Protocol)
   · Migration control
   · Device hotplug

Interaction:

```
CPU → Memory → Device → I/O
  ↓       ↓        ↓       ↓
Monitor controls all subsystems
```

</details>

