Mid-Level Question: Memory Management

Q6: What is the difference between RAM and MMIO memory regions?

<details>
<summary><b>Answer</b></summary>

RAM Regions:

· Backed by host memory (malloc, mmap)
· Guest reads/writes directly to host memory
· Fast (no function calls)
· Used for guest RAM, ROM, etc.

MMIO Regions:

· Backed by device emulation
· Every read/write calls read/write callbacks
· Slow (function calls per access)
· Used for device registers (PCI config space, etc.)

Example: A PCI device's BAR can be:

· RAM: Guest allocates buffer (virtio-net RX ring)
· MMIO: Device registers (status, control)

Performance Impact:

· RAM: ~1ns per access (CPU directly reads)
· MMIO: ~100ns per access (function call overhead)

Optimization: Use RAM for data, MMIO only for control.

</details>

